<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-630-906  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 630 906.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 11 1989 n236 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army opens competition; four vendors to compete for lucrative CALScontract. (Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics SupportSystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hoffman, Thomas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Army Information Systems Selection and Acquisition Agencyis entertaining bids from four companies to develop aComputer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support System (CALS).andO;TRW Inc, BDM Corp, Computer Sciences Corp or Xerox Corp will walkaway with the CALS contract, valued at several hundred milliondollars.andP;  The program is designed to reduce paper flow bydigitizing weapons systems logistic technical information toreceive, store and distribute it more efficiently.andP;  Information inengineering documents, manufacturing specifications andspare-parts lists will all be integrated into the database.andP;  Thetimeline for the CALS system will span 14 years.andP;  The first phase,expected to take 13 months, will involve the four contractorslaying out their architectures and detailing costs.andP;  Bids from thecontractors span from $2.7 million to $4.6 million because ofdifferences in configuration.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   TRW Inc. (contracts)Computer Sciences Corp. (contracts)BDM Corp. (contracts)Xerox Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    TRW; XRX; CSC.andO;Topic:     MilitaryContractsSupport ServicesAutomationUnited States. Army. Information Systems Selection and AcquisitionAgency.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>